# [[Par Yield Curve]] Definition

> ## Excerpt
> A [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] is a graphical representation of the yields of hypothetical Treasury securities with prices at par.

---

[[Par Yield Curve]]
## What Is a [[Par Yield Curve]]?

A [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] is a graphical representation of the yields of hypothetical [[Treasury securities]](https://www.investopedia.com/articles/investing/073113/introduction-treasury-securities.asp) with prices at par. On the par [[Yield Curve|yield curve]], the [[Coupon Rate|coupon rate]] [[Will|will]] equal the [[yield to maturity]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/[[Y|y]]/yieldtomaturity.asp) (YTM) of the [[Security|security]], which is why the Treasury bond will trade at [[par]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/par.asp).

The [[par yield curve]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/par-[[Yield|yield]]-curve.asp) can be compared with the [[spot yield curve]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/spot_rate_yield_curve.asp) and the forward [[Yield Curve|yield curve]] for Treasuries.

### Key Takeaways

-   The [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] interpolates the [[Yield Curve|yield curve]] for Treasury securities based on all maturities being prices at par value.
-   At par value, the interest rate would need to be identical to the [[Coupon Rate|coupon rate]] paid on the bond.
-   The par [[Yield|yield]] [[Will|will]] typically fall below both the spot and forward yield curves under normal circumstances.

## Understanding Par [[Yield]] Curves

The [[Yield Curve|yield curve]] is a graph that shows the relationship between interest rates and [[bond yields]](https://www.investopedia.com/articles/investing/022516/understanding-different-types-bond-yields.asp) of various maturities, ranging from three-month [[Treasury bills]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/treasurybill.asp) to 30-year [[Treasury bonds]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/treasurybond.asp). The graph is plotted with the [[Y|y]]-axis depicting interest rates and the x-axis showing the increasing time durations.

Since short-term bonds typically have lower yields than longer-term bonds, the curve slopes upwards to the right. When the [[Yield Curve|yield curve]] is spoken of, this usually refers to the spot [[Yield|yield]] curve, specifically, the spot yield curve for [[risk-free bonds]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/riskfreeasset.asp). However, there are some instances where another type of yield curve is referred to—the [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]].

The [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] graphs the YTM of coupon-paying bonds of different maturity dates. The [[Yield|yield]] to maturity is the [[Return|return]] that a bond investor expects to make assuming the bond [[Will|will]] be held until maturity. A bond that is issued at [[par]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/par.asp) has a YTM that is equal to the [[coupon rate]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/coupon-rate.asp). As interest rates fluctuate over time, the YTM either increases or decreases to reflect the current interest rate environment.

For example, if interest rates decrease after a bond has been issued, the value of the bond [[Will|will]] increase given that the [[Coupon Rate|coupon rate]] affixed to the bond is now higher than the interest rate. In this case, the coupon rate will be higher than the YTM. In effect, the YTM is the [[discount rate]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/d/discountrate.asp) at which the sum of all future cash flows from the bond (that is, coupons and [[Principal|principal]]) is equal to the current price of the bond.

A par [[Yield|yield]] is the [[Coupon Rate|coupon rate]] at which bond prices are zero. A [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] represents bonds that are trading at par. In other words, the par [[Yield Curve|yield curve]] is a plot of the yield to maturity against [[term to maturity]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/t/termtomaturity.asp) for a group of bonds priced at par. It is used to determine the coupon rate that a new bond with a given maturity [[Will|will]] pay in order to sell at par today. The par yield curve gives a yield that is used to discount multiple cash flows for a coupon-paying bond. It uses the information in the spot yield curve, also known as the zero percent coupon curve, to discount each coupon by the appropriate [[Spot Rate|spot rate]].

Since duration is longer on the spot [[Yield Curve|yield curve]], the curve [[Will|will]] always lie above the [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] when the par [[Yield|yield]] curve is upward sloping, and lie below the par yield curve when the par yield curve is downward sloping.

