## Deriving the [[Par Yield Curve]]

Deriving a [[Par Yield Curve|par yield curve]] is one step toward creating a theoretical [[Spot Rate|spot rate]] [[Yield Curve|yield curve]], which is then used to more accurately price a coupon-paying bond. A method known as [[bootstrapping]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bootstrapping.asp) is used to derive the arbitrage-free [[forward interest rates]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/forwardrate.asp). Since Treasury bills offered by the government do not have data for every period, the bootstrapping method is used mainly to fill in the missing figures in order to derive the [[Yield|yield]] curve. For example, consider these bonds with face values of $100 and maturities of six months, one year, 18 months, and two years.

 

